'''William F. Wu''' (born [[March 13]], [[1950s#1951|1951]]) is an [[Wikipedia:Americans|American]] author. He has written thirteen novels and over seventy short stories,<ref name="Pantser">{{WebCite|url=https://writersinthestormblog.com/2022/05/writers-pantser-plotter-roadster/|text=Writers: Pantser, Plotter … Roadster?|work=Writers in the Storm Blog|author=William F. Wu|date=2022-05-13|archivedate=20220513110016}}</ref> including one for ''[[Star Wars]]'' publishing: "[[And Then There Were Some: The Gamorrean Guard's Tale]]," which appeared in [[1996]]'s ''[[Tales from Jabba's Palace]]''.

Wu became a member of the [[Wikipedia:Science Fiction and Fantasy Writers Association|Science Fiction and Fantasy Writers Association]] in [[1977]] and recieved a Ph.D. in American Culture from the [[Wikipedia:University of Michigan|University of Michigan]] in [[1979]].<ref name="Basics" /> He has been nominated for the [[Wikipedia:Hugo Award|Hugo]] and [[Wikipedia:Nebula Award|Nebula Awards]] twice each, and once for the [[Wikipedia:World Fantasy Award|World Fantasy Award]].<ref name="Pantser" /> Some of his novels use robots and [[Wikipedia:Isaac Asimov|Isaac Asimov's]] [[Wikipedia:Three Laws of Robotics|Three Laws of Robotics]].<ref name="Wild Cards">{{WebCite|url=https://www.wildcardsworld.com/wc-author/william-f-wu/|text=William F. Wu|work=Wild Cards World|archivedate=20250114165056}}</ref>

